<!--DOCTYPE section SYSTEM "file:/opt/share/xml/Oxygen/docbook/dtd/docbookx.dtd"--><ns5584:section xmlns:ns5584="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.shell.scripting.introduction.whichShell">

  <ns5585:title xmlns:ns5585="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Choosing a shell for our scripts</ns5585:title>
    <ns5586:para xmlns:ns5586="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      The standard shell for scripting on most Unix-based platforms is 
      <ns5587:emphasis xmlns:ns5587="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">bash</ns5587:emphasis>, the <ns5588:emphasis xmlns:ns5588="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Bourne again shell</ns5588:emphasis>.
      We shall use this shell for our shell scripts, though most of the shell script 
      features covered by this chapter are supported by other shells, like the
      <ns5589:emphasis xmlns:ns5589="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Korn shell</ns5589:emphasis> and the <ns5590:emphasis xmlns:ns5590="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">C shell</ns5590:emphasis>.
    </ns5586:para>
</ns5584:section>